    "pathophysiology": "IgG autoantibodies with optimal binding at 37°C coat the surface of RBCs. These antibody-coated RBCs are recognized by Fc-gamma receptors on splenic macrophages, leading to phagocytosis and extravascular hemolysis in the spleen. Complement may also be activated (C3 deposition), enhancing clearance via CR1 receptors in the liver. The bone marrow attempts to compensate with reticulocytosis, but compensation may be overwhelmed in severe cases.",
